TRIP COMMENTS: Clear identification of Purple Gallinule while following trail through Mangrove swamps surrounding Levera Pond.--Alerted by loud alarm call of cackling as bird rose from shallow water and rested on jumble of mangrove roots.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Bird was disturbed as I approach and reacted noisily by taking off from shallow water some 10 metres ahead of me. This area surrounding the pond is densely covered in Mangrove swamp and other water based vegetation. It then perched for a short time on a low hanging mangrove root enabling a clear identification of its iridescent blue/purple plumage and other identifying features. Weather conditions were 8/8 cloud cover. I am familiar with this species from other confirmed sightings in world wide locations

SPECIES COMMENTS: Medium sized gull, black head, white chest, grey body, black tail, red bill
'Birds of the West Indies' (Rafaelle et al) has this recorded as caribbean coot (differentiated from american coot by white shield)

'Birds of the West Indies (Rafaelle et al) does not recognise the Spectacled thrush but does have turdus nudigenis nudigenis with common name bare-eyed robin. Having seen both recently, they are very similar but there seems to be less/no speckling on the throat/breast of the robin but I didn't have a camera with me to record.
All but one St. Vincent race (as we've seen exclusively on Grenada so far) but one unmistakable Puerto Rica race (per 'Birds of the West Indies'), or the only variety noted on Trinidad

Similar to St. Vincent race Bananaquit (size, colour and glossy feathers) but with distinct finch-like bill. No evidence of red on throat to indicate Lesser-Antillean Bullfinch and St. Lucia Finch even less likely than Blue-black Grassquit. Bluish tone was not apparent but some pictures show the bird to be more homogeneously black and sighting was in forest so no bright light to bring out iridescence).

Seen off Levera Beach towards small islands. Bright, clean white bird on both back and underside with distinctly black marks on the end of the wing. Same size as the boobies it was flying and diving with. Black marks only on distal end of wings. Same size or slightly bigger than boobies. Did not have long tail of tropic bird. Seen for about 5 min with binoculars but flew away before group could re-sight. Wing shape and behavior not like a tern. Long pointed wings like booby and entirely white back, tail, head and underside. Stood out significantly from all other boobies.

TRIP COMMENTS: There was a report from Forestry that a Grenada Dove was nesting close to the interpretation centre at Mt Hartman.  So we went there to see, the bird - the nest was within 100 yards of the building, along the trail, before the hill.  We were very fortunate to see another dove which was very bold, it turned out that the birds were swapping nesting duties!  What a thrilling experience.  We saw a male and a female tending the single egg in the nest in April!

SPECIES COMMENTS: We saw two grenada doves as they were exchanging nesting duties.  The second dove was very bold and visible while it was more difficult to see the one in the nest.  Using my phone I took a couple of short videos, but they will not load also a photo which will also not load onto ebird!!!  Shame we did not have our telescope !!  The forestry guide reported that the nest had only one egg.  Lots of traps for mongoose have been set to help the birds and their offspring survive and  prevent the hatchling when it develops and is on the ground. Anthony Jeremiah was with us.
